header.name: Cache-Control
header.description: Tells all caching mechanisms from server to client whether they may cache this object. It is measured in seconds

header.name: Connection
header.description: Options that are desired for the connection

header.name: Content-Length
header.description: The length of the response body in octets (8-bit bytes)

header.name: Content-Type
header.description: The mime type of this content

header.name: Date
header.description: The date and time that the message was sent

header.name: Expires
header.description: Gives the date/time after which the response is considered stale

header.name: Pragma
header.description: Implementation-specific headers that may have various effects anywhere along the request-response chain.

header.name: Server
header.description: A name for the server

header.name: Strict-Transport-Security
header.description: A HSTS Policy informing the HTTP client how long to cache the HTTPS only policy and whether this applies to subdomains.

header.name: X-Content-Type-Options
header.description: The only defined value, "nosniff", prevents Internet Explorer from MIME-sniffing a response away from the declared content-type

header.name: X-Frame-Options
header.description: Clickjacking protection: "deny" - no rendering within a frame, "sameorigin" - no rendering if origin mismatch

header.name: X-XSS-Protection
header.description: Cross-site scripting (XSS) filter

item.description:
An Institution object represents any Account Serving Payment Servicing Provider (ASPSP) that has been integrated and is accessible through the Yapily APIs (ASPSPs are entities that publish Read/Write APIs to permit, with customer consent, payments initiated by third party providers and/or make their customers’ account transaction data available to third party providers via their API end points).

Any one of the following would be represented as Institution:

Traditional banks e.g. Santander
Neo-banks e.g. Monzo
Building societies e.g. Cumberland Building Society

request.description:
Used to retrieve a `consentToken` in exchange for a `oneTimeToken`. One time tokens cannot be used again after successfully being exchanged for a `consentToken`. A one time token is only valid for 3 minutes and in case of it expiring, [Get Consents](https://docs.yapily.com/#e88743bc-a081-434b-b366-35370723da02) should be used to obtain the `consentToken`.

__Note:__ to receive a one time token, set `oneTimeToken` to `true` in your [Create Account Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#2d2c9547-47b2-4e0e-a6e0-73451bc4a287) or [Create Payment Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/?version=latest#8e67c40c-4b0e-4f72-947c-065f1c84f46b).

response.name: 403 Forbidden

request.description:
For standard user authorised requests, ignore this endpoint and execute a [Create Account Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#2d2c9547-47b2-4e0e-a6e0-73451bc4a287) to obtain a Yapily *consent token*.

This endpoint is particularly for creating a Yapily **consent token** by sending **OAuth2 access token** or **API key** data.

The most common use cases for creating consent tokens with this data:
- The financial institution provides API keys to access user data. This applies to any institution with the _credentialsType_ of `API_KEY`
- You already have the access token for a user and want to allow Yapily to manage your integration and [token refreshing](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc6749#section-1.5)

Note the distinction between access tokens, API keys and the Yapily consent token. An [OAuth2 access token](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc6749) is a short-lived, refreshable object created by a third party to authorise access to the end user's resources. Similarly, an API key is created by a third party and is valid until either the institution or end user revokes access. The consent token returned by Yapily is a generic, longer-lived token specifically for use with this API that abstracts multiple methods of representing consent and handles the mechanisms for using and refreshing tokens.

| Field | Description | Type |
| - | - | - |
| institutionId | The [`institution-id`](https://docs.yapily.com/#47be2dac-6881-a840-441c-b1f4ba89e010) for the institution that provided the token | String |
| accessToken | Either the OAuth2 access token _or_ the API key string, depending on the institution's authorisation flow. Note: this field also has the alias **apiKey** for this reason. | String |
| refreshToken | _Optional._ The OAuth2 refresh token string. Note: If provided, Yapily will immediately attempt a token refresh, invalidating the existing access token. | String |
| scope | _Optional._ The OAuth2 scope | String |

item.description:
The `Consent` object contains data that identifies a user's consent for a specific financial institution within a Yapily application. Other than the `id` of the consent, the `institution-id` for the corresponding institution and the user identifiers `user-uuid` and `application-user-id`, it contains various details that indicates how the `Consent` can be used.

See [Consent Object](https://kb.yapily.com/display/YAD/Consent+Object) for more information.

request.description:
Feature: `INITIATE_PRE_AUTHORISATIONv`

Used to redirect a user to an `Institution` to authorise a pre-authorisation request. Unlike [POST Create Account Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#2d2c9547-47b2-4e0e-a6e0-73451bc4a287), an `Institution` with the `INITIATE_PRE_AUTHORIZATION` feature requires the user to first pre-authorise with the `Institution`. After the user is successfully redirected to the `Institution` and the request is authorised by the user, Yapily will generate a generic `Consent` that can not immediately be used to access the user's financial data. To access the user's financial data, the user needs authorise an additional request using [PUT Create Account Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#75a4d838-ee3e-43c7-9b28-e1c100f73f1b) which will update the `Consent` with the required financial data features.

See [POST Create Account Pre-authorisation](https://kb.yapily.com/display/YAD/POST+Create+Account+Pre-authorisation+Request) in the Knowledge Base for more information.

request.description:
Feature: `INITIATE_DOMESTIC_SINGLE_PAYMENT `

Used exclusively with any `Institution` that requires pre-authorisation using [POST Create Account Pre-authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#80b7c51d-88b9-4008-949a-5abe380c73aa). This endpoint is used to update the generic `Consent` created from the pre-authorisation request to a financial data `Consent` with the relevant financial data features supported by the `Institution` and to then initiate the authorisation process and direct users to the login screen of the Institution to consent to their account information.

See [PUT Create Account Authorisation](https://kb.yapily.com/display/YAD/PUT+Create+Account+Authorisation+Request) in the Knowledge Base for more information.

item.description:
In order to access your user's financial data endpoints, you are required to obtain their consent to share this information. This information is stored in an abstraction in Yapily called a [Consent](https://kb.yapily.com/display/YAD/Consent+Object) and is obtained by executing [Create Account Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#2d2c9547-47b2-4e0e-a6e0-73451bc4a287). When the user authorises the request to share their financial data (see the flows below), a `consent-token` is attached to the associated `Consent` object and can be used in the request header to authenticate requests to access the user's financial data. 

These acronyms are borrowed from [Open Banking](https://www.openbanking.org.uk/about-us/glossary/):

- **TPP** - Third Party Provider. Your application.
- **ASPSP** - Account Servicing Payment Service Provider. The financial institution.

There are a number of ways for you to build your authorisation flows for your application. Here are some of the options that are available to you:

## Decoupled Account Authorisation Flow

The [decoupled flow](https://kb.yapily.com/display/YAD/Decoupled+Flow) is the default behaviour when no `callback` option is specified when executing [POST Create Account Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#2d2c9547-47b2-4e0e-a6e0-73451bc4a287):
- After the user authorises the account request, Yapily will update the `Consent` object at the [redirect url](https://kb.yapily.com/display/YAD/Redirect+Url) with the `consent-token` to access the user's account information. 
- As no `callback` is specified when creating the authorisation request, you will need to poll the result of [GET Consent](https://docs.yapily.com/#9307df42-da49-4cc0-8b73-dc82989620a4) until the `Consent` object is updated with the `consent-token`. 
- You will then be able to use the `consent-token` to access the user's financial data

![Authorisation_Flows-Decoupled_Accounts](https://storage.googleapis.com/static.yapily.com/images/documentation/2020/Authorisation_Flows-Decoupled_Accounts.svg?r=3)

## Coupled Account Authorisation Flow

By specifying the `callback` option when executing [POST Create Account Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#2d2c9547-47b2-4e0e-a6e0-73451bc4a287), you can use the [coupled flow](https://kb.yapily.com/display/YAD/Coupled+Flow) to retrieve a `consent-token` which removes the need to poll the status of the `Consent`:
- This allows you to have immediate access to the `Consent` after the user authorises the request. 
- This is achieved by redirecting the user to the `callback` after updating the `Consent` object at the [redirect url](https://kb.yapily.com/display/YAD/Redirect+Url). 
- The `consent-token`, `application-user-id`, `user-uuid` and `institution-id` will be available as query string parameters at the `callback` url and then you can obtain account information using this consent as with the decoupled flow

![Authorisation_Flows-Coupled_Accounts](https://storage.googleapis.com/static.yapily.com/images/documentation/2020/Authorisation_Flows-Coupled_Accounts.svg?r=3)


## Coupled Account Authorisation Flow with OTT

As an addition, when using the [coupled flow](https://kb.yapily.com/display/YAD/Coupled+Flow) you can make use of the `one-time-token` when executing [POST Create Account Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#2d2c9547-47b2-4e0e-a6e0-73451bc4a287) to retrieve a `consent-token` without exposing it as a query string parameter at the `callback`:
- The `one-time-token` is a short lived token that will be available at the callback after redirecting from Yapily's authorisation server once the user authorises the request.
- The `one-time-token` can then be exchanged for a `consent-token` using [POST Exchange One Time Token (OTT)](https://docs.yapily.com/#82712468-cd42-48aa-84e6-fbe1ee770c77)
- You can then obtain account information using this `consent-token` as with the other flows

![Authorisation_Flows-Coupled_OTT_Accounts](https://storage.googleapis.com/static.yapily.com/images/documentation/2020/Authorisation_Flows-Coupled_OTT_Accounts.svg?r=3)

## Account Pre-authorisation Flow

The pre-authorisation flow is required for any bank that has the `INITIATE_PRE_AUTHORISATION` feature:
- Unlike all of the flows above, this requires the user to first pre-authorise with the Institution using [POST Create Account Pre-Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#80b7c51d-88b9-4008-949a-5abe380c73aa)
- This request will create a generic `Consent with` no ability to access financial data in the `AWAITING_PRE_AUTHORIZATION` state
Once the user is redirected to the bank via the `authorisation-url` or the `qr-code-url` and authorises the pre-authorisation request, the `Consent` transitions to the `PRE_AUTHORIZED` state
- At this point, the user has completed the required pre-authorisation but you will still need an additional authorisation from the user to authorise access to their financial data using [PUT Create Account Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#75a4d838-ee3e-43c7-9b28-e1c100f73f1b).
- Once the user is redirected to the bank via the `authorisation-url` or the `qr-code-url` and authorises the authorisation request, the `Consent` transitions to the `AUTHORIZED` state
- This will also add the relevant financial data features to the `Consent` and then you are able to make requests to obtain the user's financial data as usual

![Authorisation_Flows-Coupled_Pre_Accounts](https://storage.googleapis.com/static.yapily.com/images/documentation/2020/Authorisation_Flows-Coupled_Pre_Accounts.svg?r=1)

**Note**: This diagram shows the coupled flow being used in both steps 1-3 and steps 3-5 to obtain the consentToken. As with the flows above, the OTT can also be used or alternatively, the decoupled flow can be used but only the coupled flow is shown for simplicity.

request.description:
Feature: 
- `INITIATE_PRE_AUTHORISATION`

Used to redirect a user to an `Institution` to authorise a pre-authorisation request. Unlike [POST Create Payment Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#8e67c40c-4b0e-4f72-947c-065f1c84f46b), an Institution with the `INITIATE_PRE_AUTHORIZATION` feature requires the user to first pre-authorise with the `Institution`. After the user is successfully redirected to the `Institution` and the request is authorised by the user, Yapily will generate a generic `Consent` that can not immediately be used to execute a payment. To execute a payment, the user needs authorise an additional request using [PUT Create Payment Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#4a20b328-2499-431d-b3fd-a3924b2f0c95) which will update the Consent with the required payment features.

See [POST Create Payment Pre-authorisation Request](https://kb.yapily.com/display/YAD/POST+Create+Payment+Pre-authorisation+Request) in the Knowledge Base for more details.

item.description:
In order to create or query the status of a payment, you are required to obtain authorisation from the user with their consent. This is stored with Yapily within an abstraction called a [Consent](https://kb.yapily.com/display/YAD/Consent+Object). You can create a `Consent` by executing either [POST Create Payment Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#8e67c40c-4b0e-4f72-947c-065f1c84f46b) or [POST Create Bulk Payment Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#0741547c-79f9-4f11-97bc-f99180211c8d). Once the user authorises a request to initiate a payment (see the flows below), a `consent-token` will be attached to the associated `Consent` and can be used in the request header to execute and query the status of the payment. 

These acronyms are borrowed from [Open Banking](https://www.openbanking.org.uk/about-us/glossary/):

- **TPP** - Third Party Provider. Your application.
- **ASPSP** - Account Servicing Payment Service Provider. The financial institution.

There are a number of ways for you to build your authorisation flows for your application. Here are some of the options that are available to you:

## Decoupled Payment Authorisation Flow

The [decoupled flow](https://kb.yapily.com/display/YAD/Decoupled+Flow) is the default behaviour when no `callback` option is specified when executing either [POST Create Payment Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#8e67c40c-4b0e-4f72-947c-065f1c84f46b) or [POST Create Bulk Payment Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#0741547c-79f9-4f11-97bc-f99180211c8d): 
- After the user authorises the account request, Yapily will update the `Consent` object at the [redirect url](https://kb.yapily.com/display/YAD/Redirect+Url) to initiate the payment using either [POST Create Payment Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#1fd6bf92-7333-4b46-be2c-1a92a3c72b1c) or [POST Create Bulk Payment Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#ef4926a7-9916-4665-83af-3168c611614b)
- As no `callback` is specified when creating the authorisation request, you will need to poll the result of [GET Consent](https://docs.yapily.com/#9307df42-da49-4cc0-8b73-dc82989620a4) until the `Consent` object is updated with the `consent-token`. 
- You will then be able to use the `consent-token` to initiate the payment
- As the execution of the payments are asynchronous, depending on the bank, you may need to use [GET Payment Details](https://docs.yapily.com/#2e1a151e-59a7-4fa1-bd5b-5f6a0c4bf4cd) to check on the status of the payment until it is executed

![Authorisation_Flows-Decoupled_Payments](https://storage.googleapis.com/static.yapily.com/images/documentation/2020/Authorisation_Flows-Decoupled_Payments.svg?r=4)

## Coupled Payment Authorisation Flow

By specifying the `callback` option when executing either [POST Create Payment Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#8e67c40c-4b0e-4f72-947c-065f1c84f46b) or [POST Create Bulk Payment Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#0741547c-79f9-4f11-97bc-f99180211c8d), you can use the [coupled flow](https://kb.yapily.com/display/YAD/Coupled+Flow) to retrieve a `consent-token` which removes the need to poll the status of the `Consent`:
- This allows you to have immediate access to the `Consent` after the user authorises the request. 
- This is achieved by redirecting the user to the `callback` after updating the `Consent` object at the [redirect url](https://kb.yapily.com/display/YAD/Redirect+Url). 
- The `consent-token`, `application-user-id`, `user-uuid` and `institution-id` will be available as query string parameters at the `callback` url and then you will be able to create the payment and query the status as in the decoupled flow

![Authorisation_Flows-Coupled_Payments](https://storage.googleapis.com/static.yapily.com/images/documentation/2020/Authorisation_Flows-Coupled_Payments.svg?r=1)

## Coupled Payment Authorisation Flow with OTT

As an addition, when using the [coupled flow](https://kb.yapily.com/display/YAD/Coupled+Flow) you can make use of the `one-time-token` when executing either [POST Create Payment Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#8e67c40c-4b0e-4f72-947c-065f1c84f46b) or [POST Create Bulk Payment Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#0741547c-79f9-4f11-97bc-f99180211c8d) to retrieve a `consent-token` without exposing it as a query string parameter at the `callback`:
- The `one-time-token` is a short lived token that will be available at the callback after redirecting from Yapily's authorisation server once the user authorises the request.
- The `one-time-token` can then be exchanged for a `consent-token` using [POST Exchange One Time Token (OTT)](https://docs.yapily.com/#82712468-cd42-48aa-84e6-fbe1ee770c77)
- You can then create the payment and query the status of the payment using this `consent-token` as with the other flows

![Authorisation_Flows-Coupled_OTT_Payments](https://storage.googleapis.com/static.yapily.com/images/documentation/2020/Authorisation_Flows-Coupled_OTT_Payments.svg?r=1)

**Note**: if the application does not have the `INITIATE_PAYMENT` feature, the first 2 steps are not required. Any calls to [Create Payment Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/?version=latest#8e67c40c-4b0e-4f72-947c-065f1c84f46b) or [POST Create Bulk Payment Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#0741547c-79f9-4f11-97bc-f99180211c8d) endpoints will return a _HTTP 501 Not Implemented_ response.

## Payment Pre-authorisation Flow

The pre-authorisation flow is required for any bank that has the `INITIATE_PRE_AUTHORISATION` feature:
- Unlike all of the flows above, this requires the user to first pre-authorise with the `Institution` using [POST Create Payment Pre-Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#76fca326-e605-462e-a7f7-ea4f4c9314ef)
- This request will create a generic `Consent` with no ability to access financial data in the `AWAITING_PRE_AUTHORIZATION` state
Once the user is redirected to the bank via the `authorisation-url` or the `qr-code-url` and authorises the pre-authorisation request, the `Consent` transitions to the `PRE_AUTHORIZED` state
- At this point, the user has completed the required pre-authorisation but you will still need an additional authorisation from the user to authorise the payment using [PUT Create Payment Authorisation Request](https://docs.yapily.com/#4a20b328-2499-431d-b3fd-a3924b2f0c95).
- Once the user is redirected to the bank via the `authorisation-url` or the `qr-code-url` and authorises the authorisation request, the `Consent` transitions to the `AUTHORIZED` state
This will also add the relevant financial data features to the `Consent` and then you are able to execute the payment request as usual

![Authorisation_Flows-Coupled_Pre_Payments](https://storage.googleapis.com/static.yapily.com/images/documentation/2020/Authorisation_Flows-Coupled_Pre_Payments.svg?r=1)

**Note**: This diagram shows the coupled flow being used in both steps 1-3 and steps 3-5 to obtain the consentToken. As with the flows above, the OTT can also be used or alternatively, the decoupled flow can be used but only the coupled flow is shown for simplicity.
